5":"1135","Bef. 1136":"before 1136","1141":"1141","1195":"1195","1109":"1109","after 1158-1176":"after 1158","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Hatch, Somerset, England":"Hatch, Somerset, England","Hatch Beauchamp, Somerset, England":"Hatch Beauchamp, Somerset, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Beauchamp","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Antoine, Jacques, Yves, Andre, Armand, Emile, Fernand, Marcel, Marthe, Remi, Alcide, Camille.","English (of Norman origin) and French: habitational name from any of several places in France, for example in Manche and Somme, that are named with Old French <i>beu</i>, <i>bel</i> ‘fair, lovely’ + <i>champ(s)</i> ‘field, plain’ (from Latin <i>bello campo</i> ‘beautiful field’). In English the surname is generally pronounced   Beecham  . Compare   Bushaw  .","English: in some cases, an Anglo-Norman French adaptation of Scottish   Campbell  , by translation into French of the folk etymology <i>de campo bello</i> ‘from the fair field’."],"variants":[{"name":"Beecham","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire): variant of   Beauchamp  , reflecting the normal English pronunciation."]},{"name":"Beachem","meanings":["English (Somerset and Gloucestershire): variant of   Beauchamp  ."]},{"name":"Beachum","meanings":["Altered form of English   Beauchamp  ."]},{"name":"Bagent","meanings":["English:","possibly a colloquial pronunciation of   Beauchamp   or   Beecham  . Old French <i>Beau-</i> often appears as <i>Be(e)-</i> in English surnames. The <i>-ch-</i> has been voiced and excrescent <i>-t</i> has been added.","perhaps an Anglicized form of a French or Flemish surname such as <b>Beaujean</b> and <b>Bejean</b>, from Old French <i>bel Jehan</i> ‘handsome John’ + excrescent <i>-t</i>. It could have been introduced to England in the 15th or 16th century by Flemish migrants."]},{"name":"Beacham","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Beauchamp  ."]},{"name":"Campbell","meanings":["Scottish: nickname from Gaelic <i>cam</i> ‘crooked, bent’ + <i>beul</i> ‘mouth’. As a result of folk etymology, the surname was often represented in Latin documents as <i>de bello campo</i> ‘of the fair field’, which led to the name sometimes being ‘translated’ into Anglo-Norman French as   Beauchamp  .","Irish (North Armagh): adopted for Gaelic <b>Mac Cathmhaoil</b> ‘son of Cathmhaol’ (literally ‘battle chief’): see   Caulfield   and   Cowell  .","English: variant of   Camel  , under the influence of the Scottish name (see 1 above)."]},{"name":"Bushaw","meanings":["Americanized form of French   Beauchamp   and   Bouchard  ."]},{"name":"Beacom","meanings":["English (Somerset) and Irish (Fermanagh): of Norman origin, a variant of   Beauchamp  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert de Beauchamp III was born before 1136, in Hatch Beauchamp, Somerset, England as the son of Robert de Beauchamp II. He had at least 1 daughter with Julianne Le Brett. He died in 1195, in Somerset, England."},"et":{"Bef. 1136–1195":"enne 1136–1195","1125–Male":"1125–Surnud","1136–1195":"1136–1195","–Female":"Surnud","1135–1217":"1135–1217","1141–Female":"1141–Surnud","1109–1158":"1109–1158","1217":"1217","1158":"1158","1136":"1136","1125":"1125","1135":"1135","Bef. 1136":"enne 1136","1141":"1141","1195":"1195","1109":"1109","after 1158-1176":"pärast 1158","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Hatch, Somerset, England":"Hatch, Somerset, England","Hatch Beauchamp, Somerset, England":"Hatch Beauchamp, Somerset, England"},"fi":{"Bef. 1136–1195":"ennen vuotta 1136–1195","1125–Male":"1125–Kuollut","1136–1195":"1136–1195","–Female":"Kuollut","1135–1217":"1135–1217","1141–Female":"1141–Kuollut","1109–1158":"1109–1158","1217":"1217","1158":"1158","1136":"1136","1125":"1125","1135":"1135","Bef. 1136":"ennen vuotta 1136","1141":"1141","1195":"1195","1109":"1109","after 1158-1176":"1158 jälkeen","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Hatch, Somerset, England":"Hatch, Somerset, England","Hatch Beauchamp, Somerset, England":"Hatch Beauchamp, Somerset, England"},"fr":{"Bef. 1136–1195":"avant 1136–1195","1125–Male":"1125–Décédé","1136–1195":"1136–1195","–Female":"Décédée","1135–1217":"1135–1217","1141–Female":"1141–Décédée","1109–1158":"1109–1158","12